          <div id="id7" style="height: 593px; left: 20px; position: absolute; top: 670px; width: 554px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_4 shape-with-text">
            <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_554_593" style="padding: 0px; ">
              <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">Although a picture speaks a thousand words, I am not sure if this will explain it all. Some asked me a few days back - Can you price an option whose payoff is S^2 or S^3. As always monte carlo might be easiest but let’s consider the PDE approach in this case. The result was surprising. <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_1"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_1">I have used black scholes PDE and applied simple calculus to derive a PDE for the form x = S^alpha. Comparing it to the black scholes pde we can have sigma bar and r bar terms replacing the normal sigma and r terms. (Sigma = volatility and r = interest rate). <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_1"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_2">So a simple call option payoff where Power Call = max(S^alpha - K,0) can be written as the a simple modification of the actual vanilla (or normal!) call. <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_1"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_1">Maths above is self explanatory.......some might derive the same result using fancy numeraires, but well change of variable is more intuitive and simpler to understand. Why invent fancy things when old one’s work and work well. My answer (although 99% will disagree, is that numeraire’s put up ur fancy MS degree in perspective, although the approach is so mechanical that hardly people understand why they are following those steps...and mostly will say “Coz my Prof. told me so...”<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style_1"><br /></p>
              </div>
            </div>
